    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To check your soil for nitrogen deficiency without a lab, you can do a simple \"fingernail test\" or a \"color check,\" but honestly, the most reliable way is to look at the plant itself first. If the lower leaves are turning a pale yellow while the new growth at the top stays green, that's a classic sign of nitrogen deficiency. You can also dig up a small root ball and look for dark, healthy roots; if they are brown or mushy, the soil might be too wet or too dry. As for the pH, tomatoes generally love a slightly acidic soil, so you want the pH to be between 6.0 and 6.8. If your soil is too alkaline (above 7.0), the plant won't be able to absorb that nitrogen even if it's in the dirt, which is why you might see yellowing leaves despite adding fertilizer.\n\nTo test the pH roughly, you can buy a cheap digital pH meter or a test kit from a garden center, but if you don't have those, you can try a simple vinegar test: if your soil is very alkaline, adding a little vinegar might help loosen the soil structure, though it won't lower the pH",
